The leaders of Australia, India, Japan, and the United States, known as the Quad, have convened in Tokyo to reaffirm their commitment to a free and open Indo-Pacific region. They discussed various issues, including the conflict in Ukraine, the peace and stability of the region, support for ASEAN unity, and the importance of upholding international law. The Quad also expressed concern over the situation in Myanmar and called for the immediate end to violence and the restoration of democracy. They condemned terrorism in all its forms and reiterated their commitment to the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula. The leaders discussed the global response to COVID-19 and the need to strengthen health systems and vaccine distribution. They also emphasized the importance of infrastructure development and addressing debt issues in the region. The Quad leaders committed to enhancing cybersecurity, advancing critical and emerging technologies, and promoting climate action. They launched the Quad Climate Change Adaptation and Mitigation Package and discussed space cooperation, maritime domain awareness, and humanitarian assistance and disaster relief. The leaders agreed to regularize Quad activities and hold their next in-person summit in 2023.